		<header>
			
			<h1>Debate intensifies on viability of Nigerian rice import ban</h1>

			
			<h4>
												21 December 2013
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>The Managing Director of the Nigerian company Attajiri Rice Mill Sokoto, Mr Alhaji Nura Attajiri, has called on the government of Nigeria to rethink its proposed ban on rice imports, scheduled to be introduced in 2015. In a press inverview in October 2013, Mr Attajiri maintained that the ban is not feasible since “local production by farmers cannot meet the demand.” He said that currently around 42% of rice consumed in Nigeria is imported, mainly from China, India and Thailand.</p><p>Mr Attajiri, who is also a large scale rice farmer, said he understood “the negative effects of importation of rice on the economy”, but maintained that “banning importation of rice in 2015 without commensurate local production would be counterproductive”. He considered that loans and incentives to promote Nigerian rice production needed to be better focused on active rice farmers.</p><p>Mr Attajiri’s views confirmed those expressed in September by the President of the Rice Millers, Importers and Distributors Association of Nigeria, Mr Tunji Owoeye, who maintained that “various moves by the government to improve local rice cultivation had not been reflected in all the production stages.” He argued that while there had been “a marginal increase in paddy production”, no corresponding increase in processing had occurred. According to Mr Owoeye, “the Federal Government has failed to engage stakeholders in the industry in the process, and this has created a lot of setbacks.” He called for more collaboration with all stakeholders along the whole of the value chain.</p><p>This followed reiteration in August 2013 by Federal Government officials of the government’s commitment to the scheduled import ban. According to officials, the government is facilitating a “massive” expansion of rice cultivation, such that “even before 2015, we will meet our requirement in local rice production.” This is to be achieved by the continued rolling-out of dry-season rice farming using irrigation.</p><p>In May 2013, the government confirmed the ban on “imports of rice via land borders”. However, according to Nigerian rice millers and traders, “rice worth around N36 billion (about $227 million) was smuggled into the country in the fiscal year 2013 (April to March), up about 12% from around N32 billion (about $200 million) in the previous year.” According to the Nigerian Customs Service, “rice worth about N27 billion (around $170 million) [had] entered the country illegally” between January and May 2013, half of this coming across the border from Benin.</p><p>Smuggled rice is seen as posing a major threat to the development of local rice processing, since a bag of smuggled rice costs N6,500, while locally produced fully processed rice costs around N11,500 (N6,500 for the paddy rice and N5,000 in processing costs). A further problem is posed by a reported consumer preference for imported rice.&nbsp;</p>
		
		
