<a href="http://www.punchng.com/business/financial-punch/rice-farmers-millers-seek-incentives-as-import-drops/" target="_self">http://www.punchng.com/business/financial-punch/rice-farmers-millers-see...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Rice smuggling is clearly undermining current Nigerian government policies to boost the domestic production of rice.</p><p>According to the Patriotic Rice Association of Nigeria (PRAN), more than 400,000 tonnes of rice has already entered the Nigerian market in 2013, with approximately 200,000 tonnes waiting to be landed in ports in neighbouring Benin and Cameroon, from where it is likely to be smuggled into Nigeria. This is partly driven by the Nigerian consumer preference for imported rice and partly by weaknesses in the functioning of local rice supply chains, which result in locally produced and processed rice being unable to compete with smuggled imports.</p><p>Consideration may therefore need to be given to the use of tariff-rate quotas to manage the Nigerian rice market, rather than the use of blanket bans that are only poorly enforced. This would be consistent with current practice in the EU for managing the rice market (see <i>Agritrade</i> article ‘
<a href="/en/layout/set/print/Agriculture/Commodities/Rice/EU-rice-market-developments-and-prospects" target="_blank">EU rice market developments and prospects</a>’, 22 April 2013) and would reduce the incentive to smuggle if in-quota tariffs were sufficiently low.</p><p>Such trade policy measures would, however, need to be accompanied by measures to strengthen the functioning of local rice supply chains and support investment in high-quality and more efficient production and processing of rice (including support to functional credit facilities for production and processing of local rice; improved and timely input delivery; provision of better market channels; development of irrigation facilities; and active extension services).</p>
		</div>
		
